00:03:22,600 --> 00:03:26,800
and to do so, they used tabloid-styled methods.

72
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:28,840
That's my take.

73
00:03:28,840 --> 00:03:31,360
Do you think there is any bright line between what

74
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:33,840
is legitimate science and what isn't?

75
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:35,680
I think there might be, but I don't think

76
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:37,360
it's where people think it is.

77
00:03:37,360 --> 00:03:44,400
I think, for instance, some people called science something

78
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:45,760
that used tools.

79
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:48,800
And I think, to me, that's insufficient to qualify as science.

80
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:53,640
So it's not because you use a little pinny machine

81
00:03:53,640 --> 00:03:55,760
to go like this on somebody's head,

82
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:58,160
that phrenology is effectively a science.

83
00:03:58,160 --> 00:03:59,280
That's not.

84
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:03,640
I think you need to measure invariance

85
00:04:03,640 --> 00:04:06,160
and measure how those invariance allow you

86
00:04:06,160 --> 00:04:07,680
some degree of predictability.

87
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:13,840
To me, that's the essence of science.

88
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:18,560
But I also think that some things that people

89
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:22,640
can discard as evidence still can qualify as evidence.

90
00:04:22,640 --> 00:04:25,800
To me, phenomenology can become a part of evidence.

91
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:29,480
To me, intersectional data, which

92
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:32,320
means it's not necessarily data that will easily reproduce,

93
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:36,600
can qualify as data under the caveats,

94
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:38,800
that it is not something that would reproduce,

95
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:41,680
that it is something that is specific to a perspective

96
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:44,440
and therefore cannot qualify as a generalizer.

97
00:04:44,440 --> 00:04:48,000
I think a lot of qualitative methods

98
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:52,280
have developed entire frameworks to explain how

99
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:55,280
to interpret what they measured as data.

100
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:58,360
And oftentimes, because people in the STEM fields

101
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:01,960
are not aware of how this interpretation is

102
00:05:01,960 --> 00:05:05,200
meant to be taken, they just see something which

103
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:06,520
doesn't seem very systematic.

104
00:05:06,520 --> 00:05:08,080
And they're like, well, that's not data.

105
00:05:08,080 --> 00:05:11,440
I was like, well, OK, to your measurement,

106
00:05:11,440 --> 00:05:12,480
that's not data.

107
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:14,200
Because there is no way for what you're

108
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:17,880
using to interpret that in any sort of systematized way.

109
00:05:17,880 --> 00:05:18,880
Sure.

110
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:23,880
But for someone who understands how to generate that data,

111
00:05:23,880 --> 00:05:27,160
how to potentially return to the space which

112
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:32,160
has similar partitions, and how to turn this

113
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:35,160
into something which becomes a little more systematic,

114
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:38,560
like thematic analysis.

115
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:41,960
And let's say, interjudge agreement.

116
00:05:41,960 --> 00:05:45,000
Then we get to something that resembles systematicity,

117
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,600
and therefore we can derive patterns from there.

118
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:51,720
So I think the line is not as bright as people would like

119
00:05:51,720 --> 00:05:53,680
to think, but it does exist.

120
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:57,280
Yeah, I like your notion of systematicity.

121
00:05:57,280 --> 00:05:59,640
Because I suppose you could just argue

