00:08:08,920 --> 00:08:12,600
And also, what do we mean when we say intelligence?

171
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:15,160
Like, are we saying some people, therefore, are not,

172
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:18,440
and therefore, X, Y, Z?

173
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:23,760
So I think that doesn't make it phrenology, though.

174
00:08:23,760 --> 00:08:26,040
That still could become science.

175
00:08:26,040 --> 00:08:29,080
And in the case of the AI model,

176
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:32,120
if it had accuracy given that, it probably did.

177
00:08:32,120 --> 00:08:38,160
But I don't think that tells me anything about a causal factor

178
00:08:38,160 --> 00:08:41,360
that I could then derive and build upon, right?

179
00:08:41,360 --> 00:08:43,680
Like, it doesn't really help.

180
00:08:43,680 --> 00:08:44,720
Yeah, no, it's interesting.

181
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:47,880
I mean, the whole endeavor of science

182
00:08:47,880 --> 00:08:49,920
is something that fascinates me.

183
00:08:49,920 --> 00:08:52,240
And once you get past the question, of course, of, you know,

184
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:54,160
well, what makes good science?

185
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:57,400
Chomsky, by the way, says that language models are not

186
00:08:57,400 --> 00:09:01,360
the theory of language, because they basically, you know,

187
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:02,720
they can recognize anything.

188
00:09:02,720 --> 00:09:04,640
You can just put noise into a language model

189
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:05,640
and it will recognize it.

190
00:09:05,640 --> 00:09:09,000
So it doesn't really say anything about the why

191
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,840
and the what would happen if not question.

192
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:15,080
It just, you know, it just models absolutely everything.

193
00:09:15,080 --> 00:09:18,760
So science needs to kind of create clear dividing lines

194
00:09:18,760 --> 00:09:21,040
between what things are and what things are not

195
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:22,000
and why they happen.

196
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:26,800
Yeah, so I think I just think we have to be careful when we say

197
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:28,440
what things are and what things are not.

198
00:09:28,440 --> 00:09:30,880
I think it's always relative to something else.

199
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:34,720
Like, I think it's true that you can put language

200
00:09:34,720 --> 00:09:37,160
in a language model and it will do something.

201
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:39,840
But will it do what you wanted it to do?

202
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:40,960
I'm not sure.

203
00:09:40,960 --> 00:09:42,960
So in the case of Chomsky, I don't think he's wrong.

204
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:45,960
I just think that in general, what we mean by language,

205
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:48,680
we don't just mean a way to transmit

206
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:52,160
semantics, I think we mean a way to transmit semantics

207
00:09:52,160 --> 00:09:55,000
which are anchored into something for which we expect

208
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:00,000
a certain kind of outcome to also follow.

209
00:10:00,360 --> 00:10:03,400
Because if both you and I mean blue butterfly,

210
00:10:03,400 --> 00:10:07,400
but we don't mean the same like referent,

211
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:09,080
then it's useless.

212
00:10:09,080 --> 00:10:10,920
That's not really language.

213
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:14,920
We're not really like converging over anything.

214
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:16,800
So I think that's the thing.

215
00:10:16,800 --> 00:10:20,000
Like the language models don't necessarily converge with us

216
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,160
where we want them to converge.

217
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:24,360
So in that sense, they're disconnected,

218
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:28,840
but they do, to me and you, carry some semantics.

219
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:31,680
And that's how we can tell that like,

220
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:33,840
they're not doing what we thought they were gonna do there.

221
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:36,080
They can get disaligned with us.

222
00:10:36,080 --> 00:10:38,280
So yeah, so again, things that they,

223
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:40,080
what things are and what things are not

224
00:10:40,080 --> 00:10:42,880
is always relative to what we're doing.

225
00:10:42,880 --> 00:10:45,080
What we're not is always relative

226
00:10:45,080 --> 00:10:48,760
to some kind of perspective that frames it

227
00:10:48,760 --> 00:10:50,900
and constrains it for it to be at all.

228
00:10:51,880 --> 00:10:54,080
Yeah, I mean, because obviously we can get to the question

229
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:57,960
of whether you think language is a system of thought

230
00:10:57,960 --> 00:10:59,640
or a system of communication.

231
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:00,920
But I kind of agree with what you're saying

232
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:04,520
about language models, which is that essentially

233
00:11:04,520 --> 00:11:07,560
they are spitting out words, which means something to us.

234
00:11:07,560 --> 00:11:10,240
And we can discuss where that intrinsic meaning comes from

235
00:11:10,240 --> 00:11:13,000
whether it's pragmatics or whether it's just

236
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,440
some kind of colloquial usage of the word or whatever.

237
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:19,040
I mean, what's your take on the first question,

238
00:11:19,040 --> 00:11:21,160
which is, do you think language evolved

239
00:11:21,160 --> 00:11:23,280
as a communication or thinking mechanism?

240
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,120
I think we're baking in the definition

241
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:31,200
when we ask for either like, is language something

242
00:11:31,200 --> 00:11:35,720
that is simply a reference between some kind of cluster

243
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:38,440
and some kind of real thing, is that language

244
00:11:38,440 --> 00:11:42,640
or does it have to be something which is externalized

245
00:11:42,640 --> 00:11:47,640
as a symbol, in which case, then it's purely communication?

246
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:51,080
So whether I think we have to be more clear

247
00:11:51,080 --> 00:11:53,200
about what we mean, because I do think

248
00:11:53,200 --> 00:11:57,360
that you don't need to externalize what you understood

249
00:11:57,360 --> 00:11:58,960
in order to cluster it.

250
00:11:58,960 --> 00:12:02,240
It's better, it allows you to confirm and act on it.

251
00:12:02,240 --> 00:12:05,000
And especially if there are more agents around you,

252
00:12:05,040 --> 00:12:08,760
I think it makes thinking much more efficient.

253
00:12:08,760 --> 00:12:12,480
So I think if we went all the way down,

254
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:15,680
I think we'd find that maybe the egg or chicken problem,

255
00:12:15,680 --> 00:12:17,440
like we could solve it sort of,

256
00:12:17,440 --> 00:12:20,880
I think at the layers at which we would recognize something

257
00:12:20,880 --> 00:12:22,760
that resembles thought or resembles language,

258
00:12:22,760 --> 00:12:24,200
they're no longer separate.

259
00:12:25,600 --> 00:12:30,600
But if we cast language as a system of reference

260
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:36,600
and reference, then I don't think you need communication

